passages.text: 1QFY26 Review: Cloud/capex beat with a renewed Al-driven narrative; Buy
BABA 12m Price Target: \(163.00 Price:\) 135.00 Upside: \(20.7\%\) 9988. HK 12m Price Target: HK\$158.00 Price: HK\$115.70 Upside: \(36.6\%\)

We attribute Alibaba's positive share price reaction on the print (ADRs \(+13\%\) vs. KWEB \(+2\%\) on Friday, see our first take) mainly to the stronger-than- expected acceleration in cloud revenue and record high quarterly capex despite foreign chip constraints, where we believe these have renewed the narrative for Alibaba Cloud's compounding growth potential. We raise our Alibaba Cloud valuation to US\(36 per share (from US\)30) on the strengthened visibility as China's largest cloud hyperscaler. Meanwhile, the company's commentaries around aiming to significantly improve food delivery/quick commerce unit economics over the next few months (which will mark Sep quarter as the peak loss quarter) and confidence in sustaining CMR growth momentum for rest of FY26 quarters have also helped address investor focuses/concerns heading into the print around the company's quick commerce investment intensity/discipline.

While we now expect a steeper Sep quarter loss drag of - Rmb31bn from quick commerce (vs. prior - Rmb20bn), widened from - Rmb11bn in June quarter (GSe), we expect loss per order to halve into the Dec quarter as Alibaba focuses on higher quality users, subsidy normalization and rider efficiency. We expect Alibaba's food delivery+quick commerce market share to eventually settle at \(40\%\) (refreshing our long- term assumption to 5:4:1, from 5:5:3.5:1, between Meituan/Alibaba/JD), and address key investor questions on the path to uniqe economics improvement (and gap vs. Meituan), cross- sell (what is different vs. prior DAU- focused strategies) and cannibalization potential (instant shopping competing with traditional Taobao/Tmall) within.
We revise our FY26E- FY28E adj. net profit by \(- 9\% \sim\) to \(+2\%\) on larger quick commerce loss, part offset by faster int'l eCommerce

turnaround pace and lift our SOTP- based 12- month target prices to US\(163/HK\)158 (from US\)147/HK\)142) on higher cloud valuation and lowered SOTP discount to \(15\%\) (vs. prior \(20\%\) , given streamlined use businesses, now in- line with our transaction platforms SOTP assumptions), while Alibaba's renewed Al- driven story- line around becoming an Al + everyday consumption app (Taobao + Amap) and Al + Cloud hyperscaler. Main Buy.

1) Strong acceleration in cloud revenue to \(26\%\) yoy (vs. \(18\%\) in Mar qtr), driven by triple-digit growing Al revenues (for the eighth consecutive quarter) that reached \(20\%\) of external cloud revenue contribution. While cloud acceleration was our #1 top theme flagged in our What to expect from mega-cap 2Q prints report, we were positively surprised by the magnitude of beat and management commentaries on expecting further acceleration of cloud growth. Accordingly, we lift Sep qtr/FY26E cloud growth to \(28\% /28\%\) (vs. prior \(22\% /22\%\) ) driven by both growing training/inference demand across sectors, with stable \(9\%\) EBITA margins given Alibaba Cloud's strategic investments (across its Al model training customer base, and to-B inference demand) to maximize overall Al cloud scale leadership.

2) Record high capex despite foreign chip constraints, at \(57\%\) higher qoq to Rmb39bn (US\(5.4bn), where we believe Alibaba Cloud's capex beat was helped by its multi-chip approach (leveraging domestic supply/RISC-V) and should alleviate earlier investor concerns on foreign chip supply uncertainties and impact to medium-term cloud growth. Accordingly, we lift our FY26E-FY28E aggregate capex forecasts back closer to the company's guided Rmb380bn (to Rmb350bn, broadly evenly split vs. prior Rmb290bn), and update our Alibaba Cloud valuation to (US\)36 per share) FY28E discounted back, from US\)30 (FY26E-based) given the strengthened visibility as China's largest cloud hyperscaler.

3) Commitment to significantly improve food delivery/quick commerce unit economics in the near-term, which implies Sep quarter will be the largest loss drag to the group, in-line with our view laid out in our everyday app battle report (with intensity to peak in Sep qtr, short-term positive read-across for Meituan as well, yet a more fragmented multiple player long-term landscape). We now expect steeper Sep loss drag to Alibaba of -Rmb31bn from quick commerce (vs. prior -Rmb20bn), widened from -Rmb11bn in June quarter (GSe), yet with loss per order to halve into the Dec quarter. We expect Alibaba's quick commerce market share to eventually settle at \(40\%\) (refreshing our long-term assumption to 5:4:1, from 5.5:3.5:1, between Meituan/Alibaba/JD).

4) Confidence on CMR growth momentum driven by adtech (i.e. QuanZhanTui with over \(30\% +\) merchant penetration, yet pace of merchant penetration uplift could be more gradual ahead as initial interested merchants may be tapped), quick commerce (which could add 2-3pts to CMR growth in the medium-term), which could partly offset the lapping of higher base from Sep (given the introduction of software service fees at 60bps of GMV back in Sep 2024). We now forecast 2Q/3Q/4QFY26E CMR growth of \(10\% /7\% /6\%\) (vs. prior: \(10\% /4\% /5\%\) ) on a combination of the above drivers.
We also dive into the top investor questions/debates on Alibaba quick commerce's

1) What is the path to improve food delivery unit economics over the next few months, and narrow the gap with Meituan? With AOV at \(20\%\) lower than Meituan and beverage orders at \( - Rmb2 / - Rmb2\) for Meituan where we see long-term unit economics gap of Rmb0.5-Rmb1 per order between the top two players (with Alibaba at Rmb0-0.5 profit per order, and Meituan at Rmb1 EBIT per order long-term).

2) What is different this time vs. previous DAU/order volume-focused growth strategies? Compared with Taobao-Tmall's investment cycle in 2023 into stimulating DAUs/time spent and order volume growth (via. short-form video content that increased app engagement, price competitiveness and neighbourhood businesses), Alibaba's quick commerce cross synergies are more direct (albeit at a much higher investment intensity/loss drag), where quick commerce MAC reached 300mn in Aug \(+200\%\) yoy (DAU up \(30\%\) ) and \(+25\%\) increase in Taobao app MAC in the first three weeks of Aug, with higher purchase frequencies, and contributed to CMR revenues. In the longer-term, the company expects that quick commerce could reduce S&M spending on user acquisition and retention (JD at a similar approach), with Alibaba's holistic goods and services offerings (across traditional eCommerce, quick commerce, food/beverages, car hailing etc.) opening the potential of Alibaba's AI-driven everyday transaction apps via. agentic functionalities.

3) Will Rmb1trn instant GMV target for Alibaba be incremental/cannibalize its traditional eCommerce? Compared with its existing c.Rmb8trn Taobao-Tmall traditional eCommerce GMV, Alibaba targets to achieve Rmb1trn annualized GMV in quick commerce in 3 years' time. Leveraging its food delivery network, non-food orders have continued to increase (13mn out of 80mn peak daily orders in July 2025, source), with growing branded merchants and non-food merchants, and new supply chains including 50K Lightning warehouses (vs. Meituan's InstaMart also at 50K in end-June) and hybrid models like Hema, Alibaba expects instant shopping demand to shift more from offline scenarios (instead of cannibalizing traditional eCommerce). While Alibaba's target will imply instant shopping industry size at Rmb2trn+ by 2028, we do note the risk of eCommerce players strong participation in instant shopping subsidies that could fundamentally educate and then transform consumer mindset (with less patience in waiting for online shopping under the 1.0 era using 2-3 days express delivery), which could mean a potentially larger instant shopping TAM (than Rmb1.5trn that we laid

out in our everyday app battle report) through substantial supply chain improvements and with larger scale that eventually could help offset the cost/logistics inefficiencies of placing inventories further closer to end- consumers. Meituan will likely be the only player where Instashopping+Ella GTVs will be fully incremental to them, while eCommerce players will admittedly a face certain level of cannibalization in our view.

market share instead of the quick commerce fight? Referencing CMR growth of \(10\%\) in June quarter, we estimate Taobao- Tmall achieved mid- to- high single digit GMV growth in June quarter. While in- line with industry NBS of \(+6\%\) , the growth rate was below JD at \(20\% + / \text{PDD}\) at teens \(\%\) /Kuaishou at \(18\% / \text{Douyin}\) at \(30\% +\) over the same period (on gross GMV metrics). Considering the Rmb11bn/Rmb31bn investments (GSe) on quick commerce over Jun/Sep quarters, there are investor debates on whether Taobao- Tmall could have achieved higher Taobao- Tmall marketplace GMV growth if the amount was spent on supporting price competitiveness of Taobao (vs. PDD/Douyin) and/or transforming further Tmall growth (vs. Douyin in branded merchants/JD in electronics, appliance categories). We believe Alibaba management's decision in quick commerce is a long- term commitment, while our estimate of flattish Taobao- Tmall underlying EBITA yoy for June quarter (vs. \(+8\%\) yoy in EBITA for March quarter) already reflected China eCommerce business group's step- up in investments into core traditional eCommerce growth.

We believe the renewed narrative on Alibaba Cloud's growth compounding potential (that is not just reliant on the foreign chip supply situation) and expanding everyday app with goods+services offerings (alongside Al- native agentic potentials) could differentiate Alibaba's equity story vs. other transaction platforms in driving further multiple re- rating of the business longer- term. Despite near- term quick commerce profit drag/impact to group EBITA into Sep quarter (GSe: \(- 53\%\) vs. prior \(- 35\%\) ), we believe the company's commitment of significantly improving quick commerce unit economics could allow investors to look beyond the significant profit decline for Sep quarter. We expect the company's ongoing investments into core businesses (eCommerce + cloud) to reignite growth, with multi- year Al/cloud upside potential as China's largest hyperscaler with leading generative AI capabilities (Qwen model family), alongside continued shareholder returns (3- year share repurchase program + annual dividend). Maintain Buy.

- Cloud: Cloud revenue growth came in at \(26\%\) , on the back of \(26\%\) external cloud growth and strong AI-related product revenue (triple-digit yoy growth for the eighth consecutive quarter). We note Alibaba Cloud released multiple updates for Qwen including: Qwen3-4B-Thinking-2507 (August 6), Qwen-Image-Edit (August 19), Qwen3-Coder (July 22), multi-modal Wan2.2 AI Video Generation (July 28).

- Alibaba International Digital Commerce Group: Revenue came in at Rmb34.7bn, \(+19\%\) yoy (in-line with GSe), amongst which, International retail/International wholesale revenues grew by \(+20\% / + 13\%\) yoy. Adj. EBITA loss came in at -Rmb59mn (from -Rmb3.6bn in 4QFY25), driven by significant improvement in AliExpress's operating efficiency and enhanced efficiency across Lazada and other
platforms. We lift our AIDC forecasts given the faster-than- expected profit turnaround pace for the June quarter.

All Others: Total revenue came in at Rmb58.6bn, \(- 28\%\) yoy and adj. EBITA loss came in at - Rmb1.4bn (vs. - Rmb1.1bn loss a year ago). The revenue decrease is primarily attributable to the disposal of Sun Art and Intime businesses, while partly offset by the increase in revenue from Freshippo, Alibaba Health and Amap.

We stay Buy rated on BABA/9988. HK with higher FY26E SOTP- based 12- month target prices of US\$163/HK\$158 on execution to improve food delivery/quick commerce unit economics over the next few months (which marks the Sep quarter as the peak loss quarter) and confidence in sustaining CMR growth momentum for rest of FY26E quarters and fast Alibaba Cloud revenue growth being China's largest cloud hyperscaler, with leading AI models and diverse application scenarios. We continue to see the company as a key beneficiary across various upcoming company- specific/industry drivers, from 1) investments into core businesses (eCommerce + cloud) to reignite growth, 2) multi- year AI/cloud upside as China's largest hyperscaler with leading generative AI capabilities (Qwen model family with the latest version of Qwen3); 3) potential domestic policies (any further consumption stimulus), and 4) shareholder returns (3- year share repurchase program + annual dividend).

Key risks: (1) Lower- than- expected GMV growth due to macro/competition; (2) Slower- than- expected monetization in China retail; (3) Weaker- than- expected execution in key strategic investments; and (4) Cloud revenue growth deceleration.

Alibaba Group (BABA/9988. HK) is China's largest eCommerce platform, with multiple business flywheels across online/offline retail, cloud computing, logistics, local service and media entertainment etc. after both offensive and defensive moves in addressing the rise in China eCommerce competition. We are Buy rated on BABA/9988. HK, as we continue to see the company as a key beneficiary across various upcoming company- specific/industry drivers, from (1) investments into core businesses (eCommerce + cloud) to reignite growth, (2) potential domestic policies (any further consumption stimulus), (3) adtech upgrade which is a key theme behind our lifting of preference for eCommerce into end of year (Taobao launched in last Aug its largest merchant tool revamp in recent years), (4) leading generative AI capabilities (Qwen model family), and (5) shareholder returns (3- year share repurchase program + annual dividend).

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
